(N'BA151', N'Indian Art, Aspects of the Curriculum and Musical Instruments', N'Indian Art: against an orange and green background an orange horse with a light blue coat is trotting at the top of the mosaic, and an elephant with flowers on its coat is walking in the opposite direction to the horse.
Aspects of the Curriculum: a series of nine mosaic squares depicting the Taj Mahal, coloured ribbons, the earth viewed from space, a drum, a lamb, an Egyptian figure, a game of cricket and bowling, a page of calculation and two faces.
Musical Instruments: a series of seven small musical instruments with various textures and colours from light to dark greys with hints of matt golden yellow are nailed to the building’s wooden façade.', 2005, 2005, N'Indian Art:noneAspects of the Curriculum: the mosaic was presented to the parents during a school open dayMusical Instruments: unveiled with the building in 2006', N'Indian Art was inspired by the patterns and designs found in the Indian Art tradition after Anita returned from a visit to India. 
Aspects of the Curriculum: Anita worked with the children to design and produce a series of mosaic squares relating to subjects in the curriculum
Musical Instruments: Angela produced Musical Instruments for the new Music Building.', N'Indian Art: mosaic
Aspects of the Curriculum: mosaic
Musical Instruments: metal', N'Indian Art: none
Aspects of the Curriculum: none
Musical Instruments: none', N'Indian Art: Anita was a parent at the school and organised the mosaic workshops voluntarily. 
Aspects of the Curriculum: was done as part of the school’s ongoing programme of arts workshops. 
Musical Instruments: Angela Cockayne was a parent at Batheaston Primary and offered Musical Instruments as a gift to the school.', N'Access to the piece is by appointment, please contact the school to arrange a visit.
See also Anita Andrews’ Fairy Mosaic at Peasedown St John’s Youth Centre, the Millennium Mosaic in Keynsham and the Keynsham Music Festival Mosaic in Keynsham
See also Angela Cockayne’s Flockat the Royal United Hospital in Bath.', NULL, 106, 405, NULL, NULL, N'Indian Art:very good
Aspects of the Curriculum: good
Musical Instruments: very good', N'Indian Art: very good
Aspects of the Curriculum: good
