(N'K152', N'Queens Road Cru Graffiti', N'Across two arches at the bottom of the bypass bridge.
First arch (facing the city centre)
Left edge of the bridge: the inscription ‘Queens Road Cru’ is sprayed. 
Main arch: from the left, there are trees and flames licking the top of the graffiti. Below, against an earthy pink background, there is a trailer with colourful mushrooms on the roof including one with menacing eyes and mouth. Towards the right there is a small green creature with shattered glass wings and more mushrooms, a fly and another alien creature with multiple tentacles ending with eyes. 
Right edge of the bridge: artists’ tags (i.e names)
Second arch (towards the river)
Left edge of the bridge: a face shouting a thank you message (see inscription field below). 
Main arch: the flame and pink background continues with more mushrooms and alien creatures including a little green man with a beard, alien vehicles, a bag with smiling yellow stars, a red river and a penguin.
Right edge of the bridge: artists’ tags.', 2001, 2001, NULL, N'The graffiti were created by young people from Queens Road Cru to develop their sense of ownership of the local area.', N'Spray paint on concrete', N'Thanks Envolve, Greater Bristol Foundation, Ernest Grand? Construction, Somer Housing Trust', N'The project was funded and led by the former environmental organisation Envolve with funding from B&NES Council. The spraying sessions were part of a summer community project. Initially the young people had planned to spray the graffiti on Queens Road where they are from but local residents objected. The location was changed to its present location in Memorial Park.', NULL, NULL, 400, 1200, NULL, NULL, N'Poor, the graffiti has been vandalised with tags added over the original artwork but the original paint is in good condition.', NULL, N'Keynsham Memorial Park, bridge under Keynsham bypass,  Bath Hill, BS31 1HH', NULL, 0),
(N'CP153', N'On the Wings', N'A series of fourteen mosaic birds of various shapes with writing on their feathers fly across the surface of the bridge’s underside.', 1990, 1993, N'A multi opening event ceremony was organised with cyclists travelling between Mangotsfield Station and Warmley Station.', N'The theme was based on flight and refers to another form of sustainable bird movement.', N'Ceramics', N'Founded by Avon CC, the roadway common, co-ordinated by Vizability', N'The 15 mile long railway path between Bath and Bristol was built by Sustrans between 1979 and 1985. The sculpture trail entitled Art and the Travelling Landscape was created by Katy Hallett with support and sponsorship from a large number of public and private institutions.
On the Wings was the result of an outreach project involving several centres and local groups such as Oldham Common Young Mothers, a Disability Centre, and Warmley School.', NULL, NULL, 150, 150, NULL, NULL, N'Very poor, out of fourteen birds only four are still covered or partially covered in mosaic. A lot of mosaic pieces can be found on the cycle path.', N'The wooden boards cut in the shape of the birds and supporting the mosaic are still securely fastened.', N'Bath and Bristol Railway Path, Victoria Road Bridge, Bitton', NULL, 0),
(N'P154', N'From Field to Fork', N'A countryside scene with a rolling landscape and cultivated fields. The scene is populated with animals, baskets of fruits on the top right hand corner, a tractor, trees and hedges and children.', 2007, 2007, NULL, N'The artist and the children worked together on the theme of healthy eating and the different food groups.', N'Mosaic', NULL, N'Year Three class produced the mosaic with David Bowers as part of a workshop to promote healthy eating.', N'See also Andrew Bowers''Pigeon mosaic at St John Primary  façade, Peasedown St John 
