(N'BA174', N'Welcome to Three Ways School', N'Hands cut out in dark blue, orange, yellow, pink and brown enamel signing ‘Welcome to Three Ways School’ in British Sign Language', 2007, 2007, N'The school was officially opened by The High Sheriff of Somerset, David Medlock on Wednesday 17 October 2007.', N'The hands on Welcome to Three Ways School were modelled after a member of staff’s hand. It symbolises communication and inclusion.', N'Vitreous enamel on mild steel', NULL, N'Three Ways was built in 2007 and replaced three smaller Bath special schools. The architects of the building are 3B Burgess, Ray Smith was consultant artist for the building and produced several pieces with students and on his own in the building. Other artists were Edwina Bridgeman, Jason Bruges, Jonathan Cole, Tim Horrigan, Lelsey Kerman, Richard Long, Cleo Mussi and Martyn Ware. 
The building received several awards such as the British Council for School Environment award under the category ‘Inspire Design-Special Needs’ in 2008 and the ‘Project of the Year’ and ‘Best Value’ Award at the South West Built Environment Award.', N'Access to the piece is by appointment, please contact the school to arrange a visit.', NULL, 560, 235, NULL, NULL, N'Good', N'Good', N'Three Ways School, reception’s corridor, Frome Road, Odd Down, Bath BA2 5RF', NULL, 0),
(N'BA175', N'Last Night I Dreamt I was Flying', N'Against a light blue background and spanning across several boards, a fox is flying towards the sky, leaving behind him a long trail of colourful stars and the words ‘Last Night I Dreamt I was Flying’', 2009, NULL, NULL, N'The artist produced the painting to embellish the hoardings', N'Stencilled sprayed paint on wooden hoardings', N'Last Night I Dreamt I was Flying', N'The artist approached Westmark, the developers who own the land behind the hoardings and suggested the artwork. Alex worked with a group of thirty parents, young children and teenagers over a two week period to produce the piece.', NULL, NULL, 200, 2000, NULL, NULL, N'Good', N'Good with wood chipped in parts', N'Bath, Upper Bristol Road and Windsor Bridge Road, Bath BA1 3BD', NULL, 0),
(N'BA71', N'Inventing a space', N'Photograph 1: a woman arranging sheets to dry in the sun on a roof top terrace
Photograph 2: an airport baggage collection conveyor belt
Photographs 3: a triptych with human silhouettes against a vast blue sky', 2006, 2006, N'The exhibition was held in conjunction with ICIA’s Symposium,PRESENT trauma/art/representation ', N'Croatian artist Ana Bilankov’s beautiful, atmospheric video and photographic images raise questions about location, identity and how many places one can be present in at once. Rather than presume any simple answers, she offers a series of observations open to interpretation. Her imagery moves between Berlin, Bristol, Cornwall, London and the Adriatic, causing you to wonder about the specific location in each image. Ana explores this uncertainty: a sailing boat drifts across a monitor screen, two distant figures walk through a lush park. In her series Found Slides, these places seem unknown even to the artist herself. Ana draws on her own experiences of in-between-ness, of having to move between places geographically, culturally and psychologically, and of living in translation. Extract from ICIA website:www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive
Part of the University of Bath collection', N'Colour photographic prints, unframed, mounted on foamex', NULL, N'Photographs produced with support from ICIA and donated to the University of Bath collection by the artist', NULL, NULL, 75, 50, NULL, NULL, N'Very good', NULL, N'University of Bath, ICIA Offices, 1 East, 2.2B office, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA72', N'Walcot Chapel', N'Three installation photographs depicting a giant seated Buddha structure, made of beige colour bricks in the shape of take away boxes, installed in Walcot Chapel Gallery.  One of the frames is made of 11 Foamex board displays with text outlining the story of the project.', 2002, 2002, N'See Chapter by Eddie Chambers in the catalogue; Vicinities – The Collision of the Global, the intimate and Identity (2002, published by Creative Arts, University of Bath) (01225 386777)', N'By building a giant Buddha within what was once a Christian place of worship, British-Chinese artist Anthony Key created a startling metaphor for the displaced Chinese ''other'' seemingly at odds with the cultural values of the environment in which he finds himself. Using plaster-casts of tin foil food containers often used in Chinese takeaways, Key constructed an eight- foot Buddha in this deconsecrated mortuary chapel stripped of furniture. The structure, in the same colour as Bath stone, was a response to an immediate environment and to the grandeur, pretensions and sensibilities of the very English, Georgian, world heritage site that is the city of Bath.
http://www.eddiechambers.com/exhibitions/index.html
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Colour photographic prints, framed.
The original installation was made of approx 6,000 plaster brick casts from takeaway carton, tinted with tea to make them resemble Bath stone', NULL, N'Curated and organised by the Edward Wilmot Blyden Project, in collaboration with the University of Bath and with additional support from the Henry Moore Foundation.', NULL, NULL, 83, 113, NULL, NULL, N'Very good', NULL, N'University of Bath, Library Level 3, the Parade, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA73', N'Diary Drawings', N'Ten drawings selected from the original series of 30, depicting various scenes taken from Bobby’s personal experience of mental illness, therapy and her performances', 2006, 2006, N'This exhibition marked the launch of the new gallery, ICIA Art Space 2 (3 West North) at the University of Bath', N'This was the first time that images from Bobby’s diary sketchbooks had been exhibited. The exhibition featured photographs of selected pages from many sketchbooks, about her experiences of suffering from profound and enduring mental health problems. The drawings were made as a way of reflecting on mental distress and the ‘mental health system’. Although originally personal and private, they have become a useful way of communicating thoughts and emotions that are difficult to articulate in words to professionals, friends and family. Many viewers found they could identify or empathise with the subjects explored, especially the hilarity that often helps us to process extreme situations. Extract from ICIA website: www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive 
The book Redeeming Features of Daily Life (Routledge, 2007) co-edited by Bobby Baker and Professor Michèle Barrett, includes a Chapter by Professor Griselda Pollock (University of Leeds) about Bobby Baker’s Diary Drawings.
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'High quality photographic prints of watercolour paintings.', N'Date and drawing numbers at top of the page some with title of the drawing.', N'Dr Daniel Hinchcliffe, Head of Visual Arts at ICIA, invited Bobby Baker to exhibit work as part of the University’s Mental Health Week and the national Mental Health Action Week as part of a collaboration between University of Bath Student Counselling Service, Students’ Union and ICIA. Bobby told Daniel about the diary drawings but that they were in precious sketchbooks. He suggested photographing the images as though on a kitchen table. After this initial exhibition of 30 images, Bobby has gone on to expand the body of exhibitable works to 159 pieces, recently exhibited at the Wellcome collection in 2009. http://www.wellcome.ac.uk/News/Media-office/Press-releases/2009/WTX053511.htm
ICIA supported the production of the 30 images in this initial exhibition, ten of which were donated by the artist to the University of Bath Art Collection.', NULL, NULL, 53, 43, NULL, NULL, N'Good', NULL, N'University of Bath, 4 East, Sunray room, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA74', N'(Be)longing', N'A series of polarised photographs featuring the vast empty landscapes of the American desert. Some photographs include portraits of the artists.', 2007, 2007, N'The exhibition was accompanied by a performance with images and slide guitar by Leslie Hill and Helen Paris sharing stories of longing and belonging against the vast landscape of the American desert.', N'In this project Curious explored ideas of longing and belonging. These photographs were taken during their road trip through the vast landscapes of the American desert. Most of the text for their new performance piece (be)longing was written as they travelled from Hill''s birthplace near White Sands Missile Range, New Mexico across the high desert mountains to Monument Valley, Utah and Sedona, Arizona.
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Colour photographic prints, framed, three as light box (in 2West)', NULL, N'ICIA supported the production of the images and they were exhibited to coincide with the Curious performance. The whole body of work was donated by the artists to the University of Bath collection.', NULL, N'http://www.placelessness.com/project/1001/belonging ', 75, 103, NULL, NULL, N'Very good', NULL, N'University of Bath, 2 West Level 2 stairwell, e-lounge at 5 West Level 3, Library stairs (West and East sides), Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA75', N'DanceSCAPES', N'A series of photographs showing professional dance artists from the South West region in their local landscapes. Framed', 2006, 2006, N'Originally unveiled in the early part of 2006 at the British Dance Editions, the biennial showcase of UK dance', N'Photographer, Kevin Clifford, combines the beauty of the West Country with the imagination and talent of the region''s most creative dance artists. The photographer explores the landscape through a dancer''s eyes using shape, shadow and light to create dynamic images to challenge our perception of dance. The locations are places of significance for each dancer and reflect many things from childhood, family, holidays, to places that have inspired works. Extract from ICIA website: www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive 
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Colour photographic prints, framed', NULL, N'DanceSCAPES was a photography exhibition specially commissioned by Dance South West and Arts Council England, South West. Local dance agencies of Devon, Cornwall, Somerset, Dorset, Swindon, Gloucester and Bristol suggested nineteen professional dancers to take part in the project. ICIA had the images reproduced on a much larger scale than they had been before. The whole exhibition was donated by the photographer to the University of Bath collection.', N'Viewing by appointment only please contact ICIA at: ICIAinfo@bath.ac.uk', NULL, 73, 104, NULL, NULL, N'Very good', NULL, N'University of Bath, 6 West Level 1 by the Lecture Theatre and ICIA reception desk, 1 East, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA76', N'Intimate Landscape', N'A series of photographs of the installation featuring small toys, objects (lorries, diggers, wheelbarrow) and people placed in the landscape, in buildings or on the rubbles creating the illusion of a Lilliput building site.', 2002, 2002, N'The Vice-Chancellor of the University of Bath, Professor Glynis Breakwell, helped artist in Residence Deborah Jones place the miniature figures featured in the photographs, into the walls of new Halls of Residence on campus. The figures bore messages of good luck from current students and staff to future occupants of the new Halls of Residence. Although the figures themselves were hidden within the walls, the series of photographs were hung in the kitchens of the new building. Summary based on: http://www.bath.ac.uk/pr/releases/mini-messages', N'Deborah stated: ''However large a place is, and despite sharing it with thousands of strangers, we each overlay memories, dreams and anxieties onto it in building an intimate and personal version of where we are. Beneath our countless parallel domains, each place is made of mud, flora and fauna, cement and water''. In her work Jones hoped to make some of these invisible territories visible. Her working processes included combining photography and drawing, temporary site-specific interventions, and exchanges of letters and emails with students, staff and members of the public. She made quiet interventions in which she positioned toys – mainly small construction workers, lorries and diggers around the campus and photographed them as she went. In the images, miniature characters industriously go about their business unnoticed in a giant University Landscape. Extract of ICIA website: www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive 
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'A series of colour photographic prints, unframed, on foamex', NULL, N'This work resulted from a residency by Deborah Jones at the University of Bath. See Chapter by Dr Daniel Hinchcliffe in the catalogue; Vicinities – The Collision of the Global, the intimate and Identity (2002, published by Creative Arts, University of Bath) (01225 386777)', N'Viewing by appointment only please contact ICIA at: ICIAinfo@bath.ac.uk', N'http://www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive-old/exhibitions02.shtml#13', 60, 87, NULL, NULL, N'Good to poor, some damaged or removed from location with marks and imprints.', NULL, N'University of Bath, Solsbury student residences GK7 opp C1.3 and D1.3, Marlborough K2 opp D3.1 and D4.1, ICIA offices, 1 East 2.1b,Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA77', N'Deborah Robinson Recent Work', N'A series of black and white photographs depicting material and equipment in scientific laboratories with traces of the scientists’ movement around the desks as they performed experiments.', 2007, 2007, NULL, N'Taken in molecular biology labs, these highly atmospheric photographs recorded the overlooked, underside, of science. By placing a pinhole camera on a lab bench for a very long exposure, the artist captured the chance elements, such as traces of human activity, in a clinical space. Rather than the clear subject/object relationship experienced in a scientific environment, Deborah uses artistic methods involving chance and changing viewpoints to record elements of the space. Through the poignant beauty of the light reflected by the lab''s many surfaces, she suggests absence and loss, and raises the spectre of the inexplicable. Extract from ICIA website: www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive 
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Black and white prints using pin hole photography, framed', NULL, N'The photographs were taken during Deborah’s residency at Egenis at Exeter University. The exhibition at ICIA gave her the chance to work with curatorial and technical support on realising the images as a physical body of work. ICIA supported the production of the images and the artist subsequently donated them to the University of Bath Collection.', N'Viewing by appointment only, please contact ICIA at: ICIAinfo@bath.ac.uk', NULL, 64, 84, NULL, NULL, N'Good', NULL, N'University of Bath, in several locations including ICIA offices, 1 East 2.2B office and in storage, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA78', N'Opposite Ends of a Possible Path', N'Sharp and blurred lines criss-cross a light grey-green background', 2007, 2007, NULL, N'Fiona is interested in the point at which painting and drawing meet.The ongoing series of work maps both a physical journey and the memory of an event. On canvas the flowing lines, preserved in layers of paint, have a generosity of scale which imparts a lyricism suggesting reverie. They are about remembering and forgetting. It is a process of adjusting the memory, adjusting the line, allowing the formal requirements of the piece to take over from the initial free mark making. In this way some parts of the image become more significant than others although even the faintest of marks are preserved like an unrecalled memory. It becomes a record of the journey of the drawing as much as the original walk. Extract from  Fiona Robinson’s page on the Axis website: www.axisweb.org', N'Oil & conte on canvas', NULL, N'The piece won the University of Bath Painting Prize and was purchased by the University in 2007 as part of the University of Bath Art Collection', NULL, NULL, 122, 154, NULL, NULL, N'Good', NULL, N'University of Bath, Wessex House Restaurant, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA79', N'Landscape Trauma', N'A series of eleven abstract photographs in muted colours depicting textures and strata of various shades and colours', 2006, 2006, NULL, N'There is an abstract beauty and painterly quality to Ingrid Pollard''s photo-based works. Her images are richly detailed, suggesting mysterious organic forms. Deliberately ambiguous, they reflect on the illusionary nature of photography. She describes them as ''focusing on the original elements of the earth, which form the fundamental substances used in photographic production''. Extract from ICIA website: www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive 
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Colour photographic prints, framed', NULL, N'Landscape Trauma was a site-specific re-configuration of existing images that the artist had previously exhibited elsewhere in a very different format. ICIA supported the new production of the work and the artist donated the whole exhibition to the University of Bath Collection. Landscape Trauma was organised in conjunction with a temporary exhibition of Ingrid Pollard''s work Self Evident also shown at the University of Bath; www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive', NULL, N'http://www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive-old/exhibitions06.shtml#pollard', 103, 73, NULL, NULL, N'Good', NULL, N'University of Bath, 4 East Sunray Room, 4 East 3 Sunray Room, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA80', N'Engrainment', N'Shadowy blue shapes against a black background', NULL, NULL, NULL, N'Part of Traject (2003)
Jane recent artistic practice has been inspired by psychoanalysis, in particular the structure of traumatic memory. The work explores psychic and physical spatialisation, not in a direct way but through looking at key elements such as displacement and associations. To be engrained is to be indelibly marked. I also have associations with mind as well as physical process such as the dying of cloth. Extract from the photography label.', N'Deep matt crystal jetprint photograph on aluminium.', NULL, N'Traject is an artwork by visual artist Jane Calow that explores the idea of a ‘moveable site’ through an artist’s book and the conversion of seismic data into music, highlighting themes of spatialisation and displacement. Jane Calow produced an artist’s book, working with composer Kathy Hinde and Dr Sheila Peacock (School of Earth Sciences, University of Birmingham) on a process that generated music from seismic readings taken from a filled-in underpass/shopping area in Birmingham. The computer programme used to translate the data into music, was specially designed for the project by Computer Scientist, Dr Chris Hinde, (Loughborough University of Technology). At this event cellist Juliet McCarthy performed 9 musical ‘interruptions’, followed by a discussion with the artist and her collaborators.', NULL, N'http://www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive/exhibitions03.shtml#15', 120, 240, NULL, NULL, N'Good', NULL, N'University of Bath, 4 East Sunray room- e-lounge, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA81', N'Durham Prison', N'Black and white photographic prints in black deep boxes. The photographs depict barred windows and hands.', 1992, 1992, NULL, NULL, N'Colour and black and white photographic print. Deep box: painted wood', NULL, N'Not known', NULL, NULL, 50, 50, 20, NULL, N'Good', N'Good', N'University of Bath, E-lounge at 5 West Level 3, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY.  The rest of the photographs are in storage', NULL, 0),
(N'BA82', N'Invisible', N'A series of photographs featuring cityscapes, traffic wardens, building sites and railways tracks with engineers wearing high-visibility jackets', 2006, 2006, NULL, N'Stephen Gill captures the details of daily life that are often overlooked. Invisible documents the activities of those workers who wear reflective orange or yellow jackets. Stephen’s work suggests that rather than making people stand out, they become invisible to the casual passer-by. Invisible was held in conjunction with Billboards, another photographic series by Stephen Gill concentrating on the artifice of advertising in urban settings and displayed on external boards concealing building work on the University’s Parade. 
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Colour photographic prints, framed.', NULL, N'ICIA supported the reproduction of the images and the artist subsequently donated them to the collection as part of the University of Bath Art Collection.', N'Viewing by appointment only, please contact ICIA at ICIAinfo@bath.ac.uk', N'http://www.bath.ac.uk/icia/archive-old/exhibitions03.shtml#15', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, N'Good', NULL, N'University of Bath. Currently in storage', NULL, 0),
(N'BA88', N'Claverton Room Stained Glass Window I and II', N'Window 1: a dark blue column with yellow and red organic shapes wrapped around it is set against a light blue background.
Window 2 is in two parts and separated by the window frame. Two purple columns frame a ladder design at the centre. The background is opaque white and transparent with glass bubbles rising up.', 1979, 1979, NULL, N'Mark Angus’ stained glass windows and panels are uncompromisingly modern, they are colourful and expressive. He specialises in commission for churches, carrying the traditions of the stained glass artists of the past who created spiritual spaces through light and meaning through narrative images. Returning subject matters are the journey, transformation, the transitions and border areas of life. Extract from Mark Angus’ website: www.markangus.de/index_en.html', N'Stained glass', NULL, N'Commissioned by the University of Bath Senior Common Room Committee.', N'See also Mark Angus’ stained glass windows and glass etching at St Bartholomew’s church in Oldfield Park, Bath', NULL, 228, 248, NULL, NULL, N'Good', N'Good', N'University of Bath, Claverton Room windows, Claverton Down, Bath,  BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA91', N'View of a Creek', N'An abstract, colourful view of a creek with a village in the background, framed.', NULL, 1998, NULL, N'Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Oil paint on canvas', NULL, N'The painting was bequeathed to the University by Miss Margaret Niven in 1998 together with A View of the Severn Valley by Bernard Matthews.', NULL, NULL, 75, 100, NULL, NULL, N'Good', N'Good', N'University of Bath, Library Level 3, The Parade, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA92', N'A View of the Severn Valley', N'Impressionistic view of fields and lakes.', NULL, 1998, NULL, N'Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Oil paint on canvas', N'Signature of the artist', N'The painting was bequeathed to the University by Miss Margaret Niven in 1998 together with A View of a Creek by Ben Matthews.', NULL, NULL, 109, 115, NULL, NULL, N'Very good', NULL, N'University of Bath, Library Level 3, The Parade, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA93', N'Creation', N'A brightly coloured piece of mosaic with numerous figures and symbols. A figure of man in an egg shape is at the centre of the mosaic; above him are a dove and a single eye. Below Man is a fish in water and a lion at the bottom left. The Omega symbol is at the very bottom.', 1985, 1985, NULL, N'The mosaic represents many Christian symbols such Alpha and Omega, the fish and the dove, Man is at the centre of the composition and a bird, symbol of the Holy Spirit.', N'Mosaics', NULL, N'The mosaic was a gift to the Chaplaincy.', NULL, NULL, 153, 122, NULL, NULL, N'Good', N'Good', N'University of Bath, East wall of the Chaplaincy, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA94', N'The Wisdom of God', N'A triptych with a circle in the middle and two half circles on either side of it. The centre of the piece depicts the Last Supper with disciples in brightly coloured robes against a gold background. The left half circle depicted a richly clad King Solmon and the right hand side half circle shows the English saint, Saint Dunstan in simple brown robe. Both half circles have a golden background.', 1995, 1995, N'The piece was dedicated by the then Bishop of Oxford, Rt Revd Richard Harries, on 2 February 1995.', N'The circular theme plays a very important part in the Last Supper scene and is symbolic of meditation. The motif is developed in the main circle of gold; the circle of the figures; the circle of hands; the circle of the table; the circle of Christ''s halo and the circle of the goblet of wine (blood). In the triptych the king is richly clad and stands in front of the temple he built in Jerusalem, a sign of God''s presence in the world. Solomon holds a rod of justice, a sign of his wisdom, while his side, which is nearest Christ, is lit by the light of the Incarnation and his left side is darker. This symbolises that even at its height, human spirituality is a mixture of both the light and the dark. St Dunstan was a local monk, from Glastonbury - he was a metalworker, a musician and an illuminator. He was also a reformer of his community, which became famous under him for its learning. All of which have parallels for the community in Bath.', N'Fabric including velvet and thread', NULL, N'The triptych may have been funded by a bequest by former University of Bath Chancellor Lord Kearton.', NULL, NULL, 100, 200, NULL, NULL, N'Good', N'Good', N'University of Bath, West wall of the Chaplaincy main meeting room, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA95', N'Spirit of God', N'A triptych and altar frontal. At the bottom of the piece are blue waves layered with light blue and purple threads. Above the water are red, orange and yellow threads going upwards and outlining a dove. At the centre of the piece is a Triquetra, a symbol of Celtic origins standing for the Holy Trinity in the Christian tradition. Above it is a canopy made of two lines forming the top of a triangle and above it are yellow and orange waves of energy falling downwards towards the earth.
The altar frontal depicts waves and the words HOLY spelt out three times with square crosses in between the words', 1996, 1996, N'The Spirit of God triptych was dedicated by the Rt Revd Colin James, (former Bishop of Winchester) on 7th March 1996.', N'The triptych takes up and develops a number of themes from the Chaplaincy''s stained glass window. These include:
Creation: a key theme in many of the world''s religions is that of God''s creativity and, by being creative, human beings are seen as reflecting the divine nature. In this context the story of creation in Genesis is a metaphor for the creativity in thought, mind and spirit that should be at the heart of a university''s search for truth.
Sea: in Christian and Jewish imagery water is often a symbol for chaos or disorder in creation. When the Spirit of God is portrayed as brooding "upon the face of the deep" and bringing harmony to confusion in the Genesis creation story, then it is a symbol of the human quest for knowledge in which a university is a crucial part.
Spirit: the Holy Spirit is depicted by many different symbols including fire, wind and a dove. Amongst other things, the imagery of the bird and its wings stands for the freedom - the freedom of God in creation and the freedom of humanity to respond to that divine act of love.
Trinit: at the heart of the triptych is the symbol of the Trinity signifying that God is, of essence, relational. God is known through the divine relationships with creation, our relationships with one another and, ultimately, in the self-giving love demonstrated by Jesus on the cross."', N'Fabric, thread and rhinestones.', NULL, N'The triptych was commissioned by the Chaplaincy and may have been funded through a bequest by former University of Bath Chancellor Lord Kearton.', NULL, NULL, 115, 163, NULL, NULL, N'Very good', N'Very good', N'University of Bath, triptych behind the altar and altar frontal, the Chaplaincy, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA96', N'Alleluia', N'A large rectangular canvas with a background of muted colours in the range of grey, brown and beige. Standing figures fill the painting, looking  in wonder and horror.', 1962, 1983, NULL, N'The piece began as paintings and drawings of refugees drawn from memories of the retreat of the Allied Forces on Calais and Dunkirk showing terrified people fleeing German armies. The artist wanted a symbol to express humanity caught in and sharing great common catastrophe. He created these barefooted, robed figures. The painting is a spiritual song of praise neither on earth nor in heaven, the myriad of human condition: in worship of sunshine, loneliness of delinquency, expectancy, carefree release in dance, etc. Extract from a letter from the artist’s wife Margaret Lambourn in 1982 commenting on Alleluia.
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Oil paint on canvas', NULL, N'Purchased by the University in 1983.', NULL, NULL, 125, 180, NULL, NULL, N'Good', NULL, N'University of Bath, Library Level 2 West staircase. The Parade, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA97', N'Sunflowers', N'Bright wild flowers in the foreground and sunflowers in the foreground, framed.', NULL, 1986, NULL, N'John uses paint undiluted working it in textured layers of colour. This piece reflects his admiration for the natural world in particular for the sunflower’s growth from seed to giant plant. Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Oil paint on canvas', NULL, N'Purchased by the University in 1986 as part of the University of Bath Art Collection.', NULL, NULL, 187, 125, NULL, NULL, N'Good', NULL, N'University of Bath, Library Level 3-4 West staircase, the Parade, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7A', NULL, 0),
(N'BA98', N'The Lillypads', N'A long frieze of large lilypads.', 1982, 1984, NULL, N'The artist is interested in the different ways we treat and view the landscape. 
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Pencil on paper, framed', N'Signature of the artist with date', N'Purchased by the University in 1984 as part of the University of Bath Art Collection', NULL, NULL, 63, 160, NULL, NULL, N'Good', NULL, N'University of Bath, Library Level 2-3 West staircase, The Parade, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA100', N'Dove and the Jackie Jones Memorial Stained Glass Windows', N'The Dove: the glass is in two parts with a dove in the upper part against an orange, purple and brown background showing a mountainous landscape. The lower part depicts an abstract shape that brings to mind a lotus, two crescents or an apple set against a triangle and a blue background.
Jackie Jones window depicts three flying birds against a lightly colourful background. The window looks out onto the garden where a commemorative tree was planted', 1989, 1989, N'The Dove: the piece was unveiled and dedicated to the memory of Lord Keaton by the Bishop of Bath and Wells.Jackie Jones window: the piece was inaugurated in the presence of the family, friends of the deceased and the artist', N'The Dove: depicts God''s Spirit descending from the peace and order of heaven into the chaos and disorder of creation. It is intended as a sign of hope to all who use the Chaplaincy and to be a symbol that God''s presence and love may be found in the noise and confusion of everyday lives.
Jackie Jones window: celebrates the life of student Jackie Jones.', N'Stained glass', NULL, N'The Dove: the stained glass window was built using a gift from the then University Chancellor, Lord Kearton as a focus for prayer in the worship area. Lord Kearton died before the window was installed so the window also became a memorial for him. 
Jackie Jones window: modern languages student Jackie Jones died suddenly of brain haemorrhage in 1989. Meryl Stannard a friend of the deceased created this piece in commemoration. A tree was also planted in his memory.', N'See also Meryl Stannard’s Dance studio stained glass at St Gregory’s Catholic College, Bath (conditions apply)', NULL, 100, 128, NULL, NULL, N'The Dove: good
Jackie Jones window: good-dirt on the outside', N'The Dove: good
Jackie Jones window : good', N'University of Bath Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY
The Dove: the University Chaplaincy’s dome above the main meeting room;
Jackie Jones window: main office of the Modern Language department 1WN', NULL, 0),
(N'BA101', N'Williamsburg and the East River from Time Square with a bit of Norman Foster', N'A view of New York’s high rises with the East River and Williamsburg in the background, executed in long slim strokes giving the painting an almost impressionistic quality.', 2007, 2007, N'Within the University Painting Competition, Piers Ottey, won the University Choice prize for having the most votes from staff and students with this piece.', N'For Piers, the edges of the picture are important, so is the geometry between the edge and the centre. The square is his most common format; primary red and blue form his initial drawing. '' Surface quality should be special'' he says and all viewers should feel free to feel the surface of the work. Extract from Piers Ottey’s website: www.piersottey.co.uk', N'Oil paint on canvas', NULL, N'Piers was short listed for the Bath University Painting Prize with this painting and won by popular vote. The University purchased the painting in 2007 for the 24 hour Library as part of the University of Bath Art Collection.', NULL, NULL, 120, 175, NULL, NULL, N'Very good', NULL, N'University of Bath, Library Level 2-3 East staircase, The Parade, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA102', N'Untitled', N'Abstract black wheels and cogs against a grey-blue background, framed', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, N'Oil or acrylic on canvas, framed', N'Signature of the artist', N'Purchased by the University of Bath.', NULL, NULL, 60, 85, NULL, NULL, N'Good', NULL, N'University of Bath, Library level 4-5, West Staircase, The Parade, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA103', N'Interlocking Figures', N'A naked man and a woman sliced through their middle front interlock with each other, arm in embrace against a soft textured background', 1983, 1983, NULL, N'Wright’s series of interlocking figures are superbly modeled, many were made in slipcast porcelain editions and had an abstractly archetypal quality reminiscent of Henry Moore and the domestic intimacy of early Staffordshire figures. Extract from Peter Wright’s obituary in The Guardian in 2003: www.guardian.co.uk/news/2003/aug/25/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries1 
Part of the University of Bath Art Collection', N'Ceramic', N'‘Wright ‘83’', N'Purchased by the University in 1983 as part of the University of Bath Art Collection.', NULL, NULL, 83, 36, 6, NULL, N'Good', N'Good', N'University of Bath, Library corridor 1 West, Claverton down, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BA104', N'Sculpture trail', N'Pot of Flowers: a round shaped pot of flower 
Fish Man: a sculpture with the legs of a man kneeling, his trunk extended forward and his upper body in the form of a fish, its head pushing into the ground, 
Figure in Space: an abstract rectangular form in two parts, suggesting two faces or figures facing each other
Commemorative Column: the base of a mock Greek column cut out in a slant', 1985, 1985, N'Commemorative Column was presented in a ceremony to the University by Councillor Eric Snook, Mayor of Bath (1992-1993)', N'The pieces were produced outdoors, in public over a 3 weeks period. The column was presented to the University of Bath on the anniversary of its royal charter.', N'All made of Bath stone', N'Fish Man: none
Commemorative Column: at the base of the column: MCCRONE-WHITE ARMSTRONG-KYRIACOU-SHIRLEY HELYAR. With a commemorative plaque on top of the column.
Figure in Space: none
Pot of Flowers: none', N'A sculpture competition was organised by John Joakes from Store Sculpture during Bath Festivals in 1985. Six British and one Hungarian sculptors produced stone carvings in public at Royal Victoria Park over a three weeks period. The stone was donated by The Store Firms Ltd and Ding and Williams Ltd. Funding in kind was given by the City of Bath College. Other local funders included South West Art, H.G The Duke of Norfolk, Julie Kent Interiors Ltd, etc. 
Commemorative Column: produced by the City of Bath College sculptor trainees to commemorate the 60th anniversary of the University in 2006.', N'The Temptation of Eve by Laurence Tindall was one of the six sculptures carved during Bath Festival in 1985. It is now displayed at Combe Grove Country Club in Monkton Combe', NULL, 180, 80, 65, 90, N'Fish Man: poor, black and green lichen all over the surface, some carved graffiti and chips in the stone.
Commemorative Column: fair green lichen on the surface
Pot of Flowers: fair, green and black lichen on the surface
Figure in Space: fair, green and black lichen on the surface', N'Fish Man: good
Commemorative Column: good
Pot of Flowers: good
Figure in Space: good', N'University of Bath, Fish Man and Commemorative Column: near the lake; Figure in Space and Pot of Flowers by car park B, Claverton down, Bath, BA2 7AY', NULL, 0),
(N'BO127', N'Spring Quarry Tunnel Murals', N'Based on a selection of photographs posted on author Nick McCamley’s website dedicated to underground cities, there are approximately twenty to thirty murals depicting a variety of leisure themed scenes across several walls that create a visual narrative. There are circus scenes, a horse race, café and cabaret scenes and depictions of indoor and outdoor games. Overall all scenes depict women, men and animals eating, drinking and in leisurely pursuit.', 1943, 1943, NULL, N'Olga and an assistant produced the murals over a two-week period using the basic colours available on site. The murals were meant to provide visual relief and raise staff morale in these underground facilities with no natural light.', N'Paint', NULL, N'Sir Reginald Verdon Smith, Chairman of Bristol Aircraft Company, employed Olga Lehmann to decorate the canteens in vivid murals. The aim of the commission was to brighten up the canteen and bring some relief to the workers who saw no daylight in the winter for weeks at a time.', NULL, N'http://www.monkton-farleigh.co.uk/sc_springquarry1.htm', 600, NULL, NULL, NULL, N'Fair to poor', NULL, N'Spring Quarry, in the canteen area of the then Bristol Aircraft shadow factories, on the south side of Box Tunnel. OS Sheet 173, W: 830689, E: 858694', NULL, 0),
(N'BS166', N'Bishop Sutton Primary Entrance Signs', N'A light green background with a flat edge at the bottom and softer edges at the top with a dip in the middle. Bishop Sutton inscribed at the top and Primary School at the bottom of the mosaic. In the centre there are two square frames with a church on the left hand side and a lake with a fisherman in a boat, a swan and a rolling landscape on the right hand side. In between these two scenes the logo of the school appears: the letters B and S intertwined. A bishop’s mitre is positioned at the top of the mosaic.', 2007, 2007, N'The mosaic was unveiled during a special celebration assembly at the end of term. It was then on display for the community at the Christmas Fair.', N'The artist worked with the whole schools to create a new entrance sign based on the schools’ logo. The two pictures of the lake and the church represent the children’s views on the local area. Every child had one area of the mosaic that they contributed to.', N'Mosaic', N'Bishop Sutton Primary School and BS', N'The mosaic was commissioned to improve the outdoors environment of the school. Funding was jointly raised by Bishop Sutton Primary School Society.', N'Access to the piece is by appointment, please contact the school to arrange a visit.
See also David Bowers’ Welcome to Bath City Farm at Bath City Farm Bath. 
